\begin_layout Title
Status as uncertainty in consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
A model for status consumption by viewing all status-related consumption
 as potential investments for future jumps in consumer wealth.
 Status is observed simply as a state of financial stability and a part
 of the consumer's utility comprising of the value of wealth as well as
 the risk perceived in achieving a future wealth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The studies on conspicuous consumption have recently explored visible consumptio
n in the developing economies.
 As a specific instance of status consumption, visible consumption is expected
 to occur through a certain type of (visible) goods that are assumed to
 be futile for the general needs of the consumer.
 This assumption has been attractive to the empirical analyses as it permits
 the separability of demand for visible goods from non-visible goods.
 While the empirical studies continue to explore more instances of conspicuous
 consumption based on identification of visible goods in various economies,
 we seek to understand the effect of wealth differences and stratification
 on status consumption in the current as we focus on the role of status
 consumption to offset observed wealth differences as it was identified
 in the first exploration on status consumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankModel,corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus instead of assuming that much of status consumption occurs through
 visible commodities (clothing, shoes, jewelry etc.) in the developing economies,
 we revisit the framework of demand with a consideration of risk associated
 with the promotion through social rank advancement so as to view status
 consumption in a more general context.
 By elaborating a utility function comprising of wealth differences and
 risks associated with future wealth, we attempt to answer if separating
 equilibrium can exist between two consumers with differing risk-aversion
 behaviour and known to have a prospect theory (PT) behavior as they observe
 a common stochastic process with diminishing rewards for risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More specifically, we consider an environment where non-durable consumption
 is both and expense and a potential risky position for a future jump in
 social ranking.
 In such an environment, the end goal of the consumer would be to simply
 maximise her wealth.
 As an example of such an expense we can consider education where less expenditu
re is guaranteed to disadvantage the individual - not both because of how
 her value in the employment market and how it shuts opportunities for future
 rises in her income.
 The utility for education to the consumer therefore comprises both as value
 in the market after a future education and the probability of achieving
 the education.
 If we observe only such expenses i.e.
 those which affect savings and increase the probability of wealth transition,
 then we can incorporate the insights from PT in the consumer's choice for
 consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this simple model, income occurs only directly through increases in wealth.
 Since references points are key to understanding consumer choice under
 PT, we consider two consumers who would compete for wealth differences
 relative to a common reference point.
 The conditions for such a game to have a net payoff for both the rational
 consumers (rich and poor) under PT - necessitate the diminishing returns
 from taking too much risk and disadvantages from taking too little risk.
 The use of PT allows us to incorporate loss-aversion in consumer choice
 as well.
 We use the solution of the model to argue whether the presence of of risk-shari
ng in growing economies that are segmented by social class could have implicatio
ns for status consumption.
 We hope that such a framework would help us answer if the consumers in
 one economy may engage in status consumption more often than they do in
 another.
\end_layout

