\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 (referred to as 
\shape italic
Sanskritization
\shape default
) as the erstwhile lower classes emulated the habits of higher social classes
 with their newly acquired economic freedoms.
 Elsewhere too, rapid industrialisation has created a disproportionate change
 in lifestyles with a crowding effect towards urbanisation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The empirical analyses of based on such studies - however - have been of
 a limited scope due to the unobserved nature of many of the factors identified
 in the studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent literature on conspicuous consumption has focused on visible consumption
 as a particular instance of conspicuous consumption - assuming that it
 brings no utility in the regular sense (see Ireland 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Hopkins-Kornienko 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The argument - often attributed to Veblen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 allows one to consider the utility for visible consumption separable (additivel
y) from the utility for non-visible consumption (we refer to this assumption
 as the futility assumption henceworth).
 In the current chapter, we follow a slightly different approach based on
 the intertemporal substitution problem - viewing snob and bandwagon behaviours
 as the fundamental mechanisms for any status utility availed by the consumer
 consumer.
 We also include wealth differences and non-durable consumption in this
 intertemporal setting - so that the competing behaviours of snob and bandwagon
 items are driven by the uncertainty perceived by the consumer.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The mutually opposing mechanisms that Veblen defined were pecuniary emulation
 and invidious comparison - indicating the trends in consumption where the
 not-so rich may emulate the rich (pecuniary emulation) or show to the poor
 that they belong to a club that poor don't (invidious comparison).
 We have found Corneo's terminology more tractable for empirical analyses
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such an uncertainty-based notion of status can be seen a state of wealth
 representing the long-term security of the consumer from extreme income
 fluctuations.
 This is the sense in which status is usually interpreted in health and
 sociological sciences literature - often tracking status with a vector
 of income, education and occupation (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a few examples).
 However, a demand equation for status goods that considers status as a
 mere demographic vector ignores the dynamic nature of status and the demand
 for bandwagon items.
 Status is essentially a social psychological concern and is often observed
 at the level of a social unit (individual or a reference group).
 So while a researcher observing a population of consumers may interpret
 the risk-adjusted net worth of the individual - i.e.
 the total net-worth combined with the risk associated with the transition
 to the highest band of net-worth in the long-term as status, the consumer
 necessarily has a subjective view of her status.
 This subjective view of status is influenced by local factors that may
 be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

averaged out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at higher levels.
 What status means at the consumer's level may in fact even disagree with
 what status means at a higher societal-levels.
 This is because the consumer's view of status would respond to the socio-politi
cal conditions that she perceives from within a particular social unit (family,
 community, ethnicity or region) than the observed variables that are standardis
ed over a large area.
 Status consumption therefore is necessarily localised at the consumer's
 social reference level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This too has implications for our notion of status.
 From a rather ontological perspective, a high-status individual is someone
 who, in the long-term, has either or both of high income and a high (inter-gene
rational) probability to move towards the high income group (stability).
 Let's call this the 
\shape italic
observed 
\shape default
probability of wealth transition (i.e.
 a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{ij}\}$
\end_inset

 representing the transition from wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

) - which the researcher observes.
 A low-status individual - similarly - is someone who has either or both
 of low net worth and a low 
\shape italic
observed 
\shape default
probability of transition to high net worth.
 The researcher - concerned with the long-term effect of such factors to
 the asset ownership and stability of income - may assume that all consumers
 observe the same probability of transition to higher state of income but
 the consumer would be motivated by the particular short-term concerns with
 respect to the social unit that influence her view of status and self-image.
 Thus the uncertainty of wealth transition is observed at multiple levels
 in this subjective formulation of probability.
 The probability of material wealth transition that a consumer associates
 with the future is fundamentally subjective - although determined largely
 by factors related to social or regional identity.
 For the purposes of this discussion, we consider this latter sense as the
 consumer's 
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
 probability of wealth transition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We argue that status consumption (other than the standardised variables)
 depends on a 
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
 (personal) uncertainty one attaches to possible future states of wealth
 and use the decision theory framework to understand status consumption
 as a choice of excess non-durable consumption vs long-term ownership of
 assets.
 It follows that the consumer's 
\shape italic
subjective 
\shape default
probability is driven by an indeterminate number of factors such as her
 occupation, education, social or familial background, personality types
 etc.
 and is subject to change over the her lifetime.
 Since consumption is usually myopic, such a view would influence consumption
 at all times.
 The notion of status, self-reference and peer effects all influence the
 risk-seeking behaviour of the consumer which are captured in the consumer's
 the 
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
 probability function.
 On the other hand, the growth in the income and wealth of the consumer,
 unlike the subjective probability which drives consumption in the near
 term, are constrained with long-term economic conditions and can be assumed
 to be associated with a different 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth highlighting that in the long-term there would be no difference
 between the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
 probabilities.
 So while the non-durable consumption of the consumers would be associated
 with their view in the short-term, in the long-term what matters is whether
 they have achieved a higher state of wealth (and thus status) or not.
 To illustrate this with an example, consider three consumers with different
 occupations in a small economy - an academic, a sportsperson and an investor
 - who all share the share the same reference point (by assumption) for
 wealth.
 They would all estimate the probability of doubling their wealth in the
 lifetime so that they may retire on the successful achievement of their
 goal.
 Given the nature of the profession, it is likely that the sportsperson
 overestimates the probability of her success until the middle of her career
 - after which the probability she associates to the success of doubling
 her wealth (if she hasn't already) would decline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus a risk-seeking behaviour would be associated with a sportsperson much
 the way a risk-averse behaviour is associated with the academic who may
 be well aware of the limited probability of a windfall in the short-term.
 On the other hand, an investor may obtain a definite gain over a fixed
 term and have a risk-profile that lies somewhere in between that of the
 sportsperson and the academic.
 While the long-term decisions of the sportsperson may still be determined
 by the knowledge of expected income, a sportsperson would be characterised
 by a belief in an unlikely probability of success in the near-term in a
 way that is different from how an academic or an investor would foresee
 her future possible wealth transition.
 If we can assume that the three consumers have the same basic needs, it
 is unlikely that the consumption of the three individuals would be independent
 of how they view the transition probability of their monetary wealth in
 the near term.
 Still in the long-term it is only their success in monetary terms that
 would track their status.
 To state whether a risk-seeking consumer spends more or less on non-durable
 consumption we attempt to understand the consumer's goal in the intertemporal
 setting (where status consumption may appear to be less beneficial than
 saving for assets).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the above outline of a model, we can separate the consumer's choice
 that would impart varied degrees of certainty - the most certain choice
 being of a cash asset and the most uncertain choices being a flashy piece
 of jewelry.
 We represent the group of durable goods indicating a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

certain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wealth acquisition as a wealth account 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 (at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 ) - which she utilises regardless of her risk-appetite.
 Thus a risk-seeking individual may get more utility from the non-durable
 consumption than the risk-averse individual (see Lowenstein-Prelec 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LowensteinPrelec1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Brenner et al and Shu et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BrennerVLA2007,ShuPeckOwnership2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for the relation between loss-aversion and possessions).
 If the long-term assets can be considered as part of the wealth that can
 be passed on to generations, the short-term concerns of the consumer (which
 are influenced by the acquired wealth) are sensitive to the degree of risk-aver
sion.
 This also means that if there is any status related utility to be derived
 from non-durable consumption, it would be constituted in the felicity from
 its excess quantity with respect to one's reference group.
 This is simply because a consumer with a habit of high quality in regular
 consumption would 
\shape italic
ceteris paribus 
\shape default
have higher status than another consumer consuming less quality.
 The fulfilment of basic consumer needs itself carries no influence on status.
 It follows that if we were to compare the consumption of a risk-seeking
 consumers with that of a risk-averse consumer, the consumption on needs
 would not have any role to play in the utility relative to one another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we associate non-durable consumption with the subjective probability,
 the status-related consumption (seen as high non-durable consumption) is
 exhibited as a risk-seeking behaviour i.e.
 when the 
\shape italic
subjective 
\shape default
probability is much higher than the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probability.
 Those who are hoping to enhance their social network or get ahead of others
 through signaling (or peer effects) are likely to believe in a higher likelihoo
d of their promotion to a higher status.
 A higher probability for the state promotion perceived by a risk-seeking
 consumer would thus result in a higher utility for the same observed probabilit
y.
 Similarly, the perceived probability of loss of one's status would be higher
 (e.g.
 that of threat of immigration to one's personal wealth) than the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probability in the long-term for a risk-averse consumer.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The arguments for subjective probability that we use to develop our status
 consumption model have been around at least since Keynes.
 A more formal treatment of subjective probability is offered by de Finetti
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vonPlato2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Savage
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Savage1972"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 .
 The term personal probability (instead of perceived probability) is used
 by Savage to imply a probability associated with a consequence.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It may be worthwhile to hypothesise the economic processes that are implied
 by an interplay of the two levels of uncertainties that we use to separate
 the uncertainty in observed economic variables from the degrees of risk-aversio
n exhibited amongst consumers.
 One way to view the two uncertainties is as a delay or barriers in the
 flow of information related to risks in the consumer markets.
 When it comes to risks to the future wealth, the firms and institutions
 are often both better equipped and more responsive than the individuals
 or small communities.
 The differences in subjective uncertainties and observed uncertainties
 only because of the differences in how information is consumed at different
 levels of societal organisation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The barrier to information may help elucidate the limits to the free-market
 assumption which considers an autonomous consumer fully capable of addressing
 her true needs (see a discussion in Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 There is little doubt that the differences in purchasing power between
 sections of a society and their desire for mobility can drive the consumption
 and the economy (see Smith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SmithMoralSentiments"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 But the implicit assumption in the free market view of an exchange between
 the rich and poor sections driving economic progress is that the consumer
 has full information of the risks and incentives related to her wealth
 (i.e.
 the economy functions in a way that these risks are known to the consumer).
 The barriers to the flow of information with a growing strength of institutions
 - which a consideration of the two uncertainties which we attempt to model
 - could partly explain why this exchange may be less feasible in more recent
 times (see Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Galbraith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GalbraithEssential,GalbraithAffluent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This effect would be particularly visible in the economies undergoing structura
l changes such as rapid industrialisation, higher advertising effects or
 centralisation of markets.
 As long as it can be admitted that the information about socio-economic
 changes is consumed at different speeds and extent amongst the consumers
 than firms then it must follow that the information of risks is not considered
 fully by the consumer.
 Thus the consumption in the short-term is likely to be influenced by asymmetrie
s in the observation of risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the model to be of any empirical utility, it must be acknowledge that
 the beliefs of the consumers converge to the observed economic variables
 in the long run.
 The resources in the world evolve as they are influenced by the actions
 taken on beliefs rather than beliefs themselves.
 In the long-run, the consumer beliefs reflect the changes in long-term
 assets by letting the risk-averse behaviours balance the risk-seeking behaviour
s in participate in the same economy.
 Thus the consumers' subjective probability functions are reconciled with
 an observed trajectory of wealth over a sufficiently long-period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It may be worthwhile at this point to compare the approach we've taken with
 the permanent income hypothesis (PIH).
 The fundamental claim of the PIH is that income has a transitory and a
 permanent component where the consumption is directly proportional to the
 permanent component
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The observed income of an individual (household) is the sum of transitory
 and permanent income components
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - so that the low-income individual may have too much uncertainty with
 her income - requiring her to maintain buffer stocks for her needs.
 Like in PIH, we also rely on a certain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cancellation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of short-term fluctuations in the long-run and recognise the role of inheritanc
e (which PIH views as an increase in the permanent income).
